Feature: Standardise Alert Controllers & Handle WebSocket Messages App-Wide

🧠 Overview

Two related gaps exist in the current iOS codebase:

1. Alert Controllers (UIKit-wide)
   - `presentAlert(withTitle:message:)` and `presentAlertWithFunction(withTitle:message:function:)`
     are defined as `UIViewController` extension methods in `HomeVC.swift`.
   - They are called across `BasketVC`, `MenuVC`, `PurchasesVC`, `SignupVC` —
     any VC that inherits `UIViewController` picks them up — but:
     - The definition lives in a file named after a specific VC (`HomeVC.swift`),
       making it hard to find and maintain.
     - There is no SwiftUI equivalent — any future SwiftUI view that needs
       to show an alert must reinvent the pattern.
     - `presentAlertWithFunction` hardcodes `"sendEmail"` as a magic string
       and mixes presentation logic with business logic (triggering activation).
     - No `.destructive` or multi-action alert pattern exists yet.

2. WebSocket Incoming Messages (no UI handling)
   - `WebSocketManager.receiveMessage()` receives server-sent messages and only
     calls `print()` — the message content is discarded.
   - The backend broadcasts seat-availability updates via Kafka → WebSocket
     after a booking completes (see `mbooks-quarkus` `WebSocketServer.broadcast()`).
   - No VC or view currently observes these messages to refresh the seat map
     or notify the user.

This feature:
- Extracts alert helpers into a dedicated, reusable file (`AlertPresenter.swift`)
- Defines a typed `AlertMessage` model instead of loose title/message strings
- Provides a SwiftUI-compatible `AlertItem` binding pattern
- Wires `WebSocketManager` to publish incoming messages via `Combine` / `@Published`
  so any observing view can react (refresh seat map, show alert)

